m is the average mass of the up and down quarks, and m is that of the strange one. These
s




formulae are obtained both in the quark model and in the chiral quark model. The main point I wish


to stress is that these are theoretical formulae which should be tested experimentally. The simplest


direct tests are in semileptonic decays of hyperons which have a 7 or E° in the initial or final state.

%
One such test involves the semileptonic decay of a charged E, say E to a 7. If isospin is


conserved, the vector coupling vanishes [3], but with the mixing taken into consideration one finds


[1,4]:


g / g ' 3 tanN ' 3 N ï &0.03
